2026-03-31 08:33:40,480 INFO [llm] rag.ask returned repr: {'answer': '# SUMMARY, DIAGNOSIS, AND ACTION PLAN\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe plant experienced an overall cost increase of **0.43 €/t** (reaching 279.59 €/t), driven primarily by an unfavorable grade mix (+0.34 €/t) and process deterioration (+0.09 €/t). Individual grade performance varied significantly, with grade 6010085 showing the largest cost increase (+4.40 €/t) and grade 3200115 achieving the strongest cost reduction (-5.26 €/t). Overall overprocessing increased by 1.22% to 7.45%, indicating quality targets are being exceeded unnecessarily, particularly in strength properties (SCT_CD, CMT30, Burst).\n\n---\n\n## Diagnosis by Section\n\n### Stock Preparation & Wet End Section\n\n**Key Variables & Purpose:**\n- **Retention** (Wet End): Measures fiber and filler capture efficiency in sheet formation\n- **Retention Aid mass flow g/T** (Chemical Additives): Polymer dosage to improve retention\n- **Consistency white water** (Short Circulation): Solids content in recirculated water\n- **Jet/wire ratio** (Forming Section): Headbox jet speed vs. wire speed ratio affecting formation\n\n**Findings:**\n- Grade 6010100 and 6010120 show significant increases in retention aid usage (+53.26 g/T and +30.04 g/T respectively), indicating retention problems\n- Jet/wire ratio decreased significantly in grades 6010085 (-2.57) and 6010100 (-20.41), suggesting formation issues\n- White water consistency variations indicate unstable short circulation conditions\n\n**Root Causes:**\nAccording to [papermaking_science_technology.pdf:d6f6f20ccb65b658:4602:0], "A change in the retention level will cause a change in the level of paper ash. Filler flow is generally changed in advance and also the dosing of retention chemical may be adjusted accordingly." The data suggests grade changes are causing retention instability, requiring excessive chemical compensation.\n\n### Pressing Section\n\n**Key Variables & Purpose:**\n- **Vacuum uhle-box bottom felt** (Press Section): Vacuum level for water removal through felt\n- **Linepressure (1st press DS, shoe press)** (Press Section): Mechanical pressure for dewatering\n- **Rod pressure Top Roll** (Size Press): Pressure controlling starch application\n- **Vacuum presszone of suction-press roll** (Press Section): Vacuum-assisted pressing\n\n**Findings:**\n- Vacuum adjustments in press section show inconsistent patterns across grades\n- Rod pressure reductions in grades 6010085 (-1.45) and 6010120 (-0.57) correlate with starch application issues\n- Line pressure increases suggest attempts to compensate for upstream dewatering problems\n\n### Drying Section\n\n**Key Variables & Purpose:**\n- **DG1, DG4 Temperature Inlet Air** (Drying Section): Hood air temperature for evaporation\n- **Cylinder 37 steam pressure** (Drying Section): Steam pressure in drying cylinders\n- **Current reel moisture average** (Drying Section): Final paper moisture content\n- **Speed/Speed PD1** (Machine Control): Paper machine operating speed\n\n**Findings:**\n- Major drying temperature variations: Grade 6010085 shows DG4 increase (+15.57°C) while grades 3200115 and 6010120 show significant decreases (-12.23°C and -33.89°C)\n- Steam pressure reductions in grades 3200115 (-0.42 bar) and 6010120 (-0.25 bar) indicate drying inefficiencies\n- Reel moisture increases in grades 6010085 (+0.72%) and 6010120 (+0.37%) are cost-reducing but may indicate over-drying previously\n\n**Root Causes:**\nPer [papermaking_science_technology.pdf:d6f6f20ccb65b658:4601:0], "The purpose of changing the steam pressure is to feed the required amount of heat to the cylinders in order to minimise temperature and heat flow fluctuations." The erratic temperature patterns suggest poor grade change management and steam system optimization.\n\n### Size Press Section\n\n**Key Variables & Purpose:**\n- **Starch uptake g/m²** (Size Press): Total starch applied to paper\n- **Starch uptake by paper Top/Bottom Roll 